P R O B L E M S T A T E M E N T -¶

Predicting the Re-admission possibility of a patient into the hospital & Pattern Extraction.

B U I S N E S S -- P R O B L E M¶

Before we look at ways to address the issue, let's first understand what "Hospital Readmission" is exactly. A hospital readmission is an episode when a patient who had been discharged from a hospital is admitted again within a specified time interval. Readmission rates have increasingly been used as an outcome measure in health services research and as a quality benchmark for health systems. Though th medical and health services literature has a variety of definitions of definitions of readmissions, the Centres of Medicare and Medicaid services has created a stricter set of criteria. CMS defines a hospital readmission as "an admission to an acute care hospital within 30 days of discharge from the same or another acute care hospital. It uses an "all-cause" definition, meaning that the cause of the readmission does not need to be related to the cause of the initial hospitalization. The time frame was set at 30 days because readmissions during this time can be influenced by the quality of care recieved at the hospital and how well discharges were coordinated.

Now, given the dataset it is crucial to understand what are the possible factors that influence readmission. There are several attributes to each inpatient entry along with their demographic data. PROBLEM AT HAND - The policy, known as the "Hospital Readmissions Reduction Program", creates financial penalties for hospital whose readmissions exceed the national average. It's aim was to encourage hospitals to deliver stepped-up care for severly ill patients even after they leave the hospital, in the hope of preventing return visits that result in more pain/anguish for patients and skyrocketing for everyone else.

M L -- P R O B L E M¶

The hospital has two types of admissions -

  1. people who have not been readmitted
  2. Peopl who have been readmitted WITHIN 30 days.

The hospitals require a tool which can help them predict a readmission of a patient based on the initial admission. Therefore, this is a Classification problem where the model should be able to predict & classify patients as either not readmitted or will be readmitted within 30 days. This will help hospitals address two problems -

  1. Be ready to address patients appropriately in the first admission based on prediction.
  2. Eventually, the hospitals will be able to pin point the key issues which result in patient readmissions which arise due to quality of care being provided at the hospital for patients who have been predicted as "will be readmitted".

BASE -- PROBLEMS BEING ADDRESSED -¶

  1. To avoid penalties on hospitals which will result in high fees for patients eventually.
  2. To reduce the impact of readmission costs on the insurance firms providing healthcare benefits for patients.
  3. To increase the quality of care provided by the hospitals for the patients.

A function to bin the diagnosis column, based on description given on ICD codes - 9 online.

The following is a list of codes for International Statistical Classification of Diseases and Related Health Problems - for reference in the figure.¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 001–139: infectious and parasitic diseases¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 140–239: neoplasms¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 240–279: endocrine, nutritional and metabolic diseases, and immunity disorders¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 280–289: diseases of the blood and blood-forming organs¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 290–319: mental disorders¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 320–389: diseases of the nervous system and sense organs¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 390–459: diseases of the circulatory system¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 460–519: diseases of the respiratory system¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 520–579: diseases of the digestive system¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 580–629: diseases of the genitourinary system¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 630–679: complications of pregnancy, childbirth, and the puerperium¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 680–709: diseases of the skin and subcutaneous tissue¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 710–739: diseases of the musculoskeletal system and connective tissue¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 740–759: congenital anomalies¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 760–779: certain conditions originating in the perinatal period¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 780–799: symptoms, signs, and ill-defined conditions¶

-List of ICD-9 codes 800–999: injury and poisoning¶

-List of ICD-9 codes E and V codes: external causes of injury and supplemental classification¶

Source - wikipedia¶

def bin_diagnosis(col):
    diagnosis = pd.Series([])
    for i, item in enumerate(col):
        if(item[0] == 'E' or item[0] == 'V'):
            diagnosis[i] = '17'
        else:
            x = float(item)
            if(x < 140):
                diagnosis[i] = '1'
            elif(x >= 140 and x < 240):
                diagnosis[i] = '2'
            elif(x >= 240 and x < 280):
                diagnosis[i] = '3'
            elif(x >=280 and x < 290):
                diagnosis[i] = '4'
            elif(x >=290 and x <= 319):
                diagnosis[i] = '5'
            elif(x >= 320 and x < 390):
                diagnosis[i] = '6'
            elif(x >= 390 and x < 460):
                diagnosis[i] = '7'
            elif(x >= 520 and x < 580):
                diagnosis[i] = '8'
            elif(x >= 580 and x < 630):
                diagnosis[i] = '9'
            elif(x >= 630 and x < 677):
                diagnosis[i] = '10'
            elif(x >= 677 and x < 710):
                diagnosis[i] = '11'
            elif(x >= 710 and x < 740):
                diagnosis[i] = '12'
            elif(x >= 740 and x < 760):
                diagnosis[i] = '13'
            elif(x >= 760 and x < 780):
                diagnosis[i] = '14'
            elif(x >= 780 and x < 800):
                diagnosis[i] = '15'
            else:
                diagnosis[i] = '16'
        
    print(len(diagnosis))
        
    return diagnosis

def seperate_cat_num(data):
    cat_Var_Names = []
    num_Var_Names = []
    for i in data.columns:
        if(data[i].dtypes=="object"):
            cat_Var_Names.append(i)
        else:
                num_Var_Names.append(i)
    return cat_Var_Names,num_Var_Names

UPSAMPLING OF full Train data for best prediction on actual test data¶

In [52]:
from sklearn.utils import resample


# concatenate our training data back together
X = pd.concat([X_final, y_final], axis=1)

# separate minority and majority classes
not_re_admitted = X[X.readmitted==0]
readmitted = X[X.readmitted==1]

# upsample minority
readmission_upsampled = resample(readmitted,
                          replace=True, # sample with replacement
                          n_samples=len(not_re_admitted), # match number in majority class
                          random_state=1) # reproducible results

# combine majority and upsampled minority
final_df = pd.concat([not_re_admitted, readmission_upsampled])

# check new class counts
final_df.readmitted.value_counts()

THE -- M E T R I C -- THING:¶

The given metric for the problem statement is 'recall', which makes sense as one would like to rather focus on increasing the count of predictions for the class of people getting readmitted. However, as one tends to increase the recall for one class, accuracy tends to go down, logically. The most optimised model here would be the one which can increase the recall for our desired calss while maintaining accuracy at a decent level. Now, it is also important that we predict the desired class as precisely as possible. To ensure this we shall look at precision scores for all models as well.

CONFUSION MATRIX¶

In [54]:
Image(filename='M:/Bckup/aft_cllg/PHD/PHD_Last_act/PLOTS/conf_mat.png')
Out[54]:

• Positive (P) : Observation is positive (for example: is an apple).¶

• Negative (N) : Observation is not positive (for example: is not an apple).¶

• True Positive (TP) : Observation is positive, and is predicted to be positive.¶

• False Negative (FN) : Observation is positive, but is predicted negative.¶

• True Negative (TN) : Observation is negative, and is predicted to be negative.¶

• False Positive (FP) : Observation is negative, but is predicted positive.¶

Accuracy = (TP + TN) / (TP + TN + FP +FN)¶
Recall = TP / (TP + FN)¶
Precision = TP / (TP + FP) - high recall, low precision problem and vice-versa.¶
The given data set also has a huge class imbalance issue. Upsampling will be used to train the model to deal with this issue. A function to check prevalance will also be employed in order to validate the training. One can't expect a model which has been trained on 14% of a particular to class to be good at classification.¶
In [55]:
def calc_prevalence(y_actual):
    return (sum(y_actual)/len(y_actual))
All the functions have been joined under one function - print_report.¶
In [56]:
from sklearn.metrics import roc_auc_score, accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score
def calc_specificity(y_actual, y_pred, thresh):
    # calculates specificity
    return sum((y_pred < thresh) & (y_actual == 0)) /sum(y_actual ==0)

def print_report(y_actual, y_pred, thresh):
    
    auc = roc_auc_score(y_actual, y_pred)
    accuracy = accuracy_score(y_actual, (y_pred > thresh))
    recall = recall_score(y_actual, (y_pred > thresh))
    precision = precision_score(y_actual, (y_pred > thresh))
    specificity = calc_specificity(y_actual, y_pred, thresh)
    print('AUC:%.3f'%auc)
    print('accuracy:%.3f'%accuracy)
    print('recall:%.3f'%recall)
    print('precision:%.3f'%precision)
    print('specificity:%.3f'%specificity)
    print('prevalence:%.3f'%calc_prevalence(y_actual))
    print(' ')
    return auc, accuracy, recall, precision, specificity

In [60]:
import numpy as np
from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve
from sklearn.model_selection import ShuffleSplit

def plot_learning_curve(estimator, title, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None,
                        n_jobs=1, train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5)):
    """
    Generate a simple plot of the test and training learning curve.

    Parameters
    ----------
    estimator : object type that implements the "fit" and "predict" methods
        An object of that type which is cloned for each validation.

    title : string
        Title for the chart.

    X : array-like, shape (n_samples, n_features)
        Training vector, where n_samples is the number of samples and
        n_features is the number of features.

    y : array-like, shape (n_samples) or (n_samples, n_features), optional
        Target relative to X for classification or regression;
        None for unsupervised learning.

    ylim : tuple, shape (ymin, ymax), optional
        Defines minimum and maximum yvalues plotted.

    cv : int, cross-validation generator or an iterable, optional
        Determines the cross-validation splitting strategy.
        Possible inputs for cv are:
          - None, to use the default 3-fold cross-validation,
          - integer, to specify the number of folds.
          - An object to be used as a cross-validation generator.
          - An iterable yielding train/test splits.

        For integer/None inputs, if ``y`` is binary or multiclass,
        :class:`StratifiedKFold` used. If the estimator is not a classifier
        or if ``y`` is neither binary nor multiclass, :class:`KFold` is used.

        Refer :ref:`User Guide <cross_validation>` for the various
        cross-validators that can be used here.

    n_jobs : integer, optional
        Number of jobs to run in parallel (default 1).
    """
    plt.figure()
    plt.title(title)
    if ylim is not None:
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
    plt.xlabel("Training examples")
    plt.ylabel("AUC")
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
        estimator, X, y, cv=cv, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes, scoring = 'roc_auc')
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    plt.grid()

    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,
                     train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,
                     color="r")
    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,
                     test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="b")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",
             label="Training score")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="b",
             label="Cross-validation score")

    plt.legend(loc="best")
    return plt

# concatenate our training data back together
X = pd.concat([X_train, y_train], axis=1)

# separate minority and majority classes

readmitted = X[X.readmitted==1]

                          replace=True, # sample with replacement
                          n_samples=len(not_re_admitted), # match number in majority class
                          random_state=1) # reproducible results

from sklearn.model_selection import RandomizedSearchCV

# number of trees
n_estimators = range(200,1000,200)
# maximum number of features to use at each split
max_features = ['auto','sqrt']
# maximum depth of the tree
max_depth = range(1,10,1)
# minimum number of samples to split a node
min_samples_split = range(2,10,2)
# criterion for evaluating a split
criterion = ['gini','entropy']

# random grid

random_grid = {'n_estimators':n_estimators,
              'max_features':max_features,
              'max_depth':max_depth,
              'min_samples_split':min_samples_split,
              'criterion':criterion}

Based on the above results from the respective models.¶

Gridcv_xgb with a recall of 61 and an accuracy of 57. This the most decent result. All the other results have a bias towards either recall or accuracy.

If we can choose a tradeoff between accuracy and recall and prefer recall. Then Randomised SGDC, followed by Naive Bayes, followed by Simple decision tree models also work fine.

What the confusion matrix means for us here.¶

true positives (TP): These are cases in which we predicted yes (they have the disease), and they do have the disease.¶
true negatives (TN): We predicted no, and they don't have the disease.¶
false positives (FP): We predicted yes, but they don't actually have the disease. (Also known as a "Type I error.")¶
false negatives (FN): We predicted no, but they actually do have the disease. (Also known as a "Type II error.")¶
Accuracy: Overall, how often is the classifier correct?¶

(TP+TN)/total - All my models here have a range of accuracies. However, as accuracy increases, recall starts to decrease.

Misclassification Rate: Overall, how often is it wrong?¶

(FP+FN)/total -

True Positive Rate: When it's actually yes, how often does it predict yes?¶

TP/actual yes - In our model, class 1 recall should be high. also known as "Sensitivity" or "Recall"

False Positive Rate: When it's actually no, how often does it predict yes?¶

FP/actual no -

True Negative Rate: When it's actually no, how often does it predict no?¶

TN/actual no equivalent to 1 minus False Positive Rate also known as "Specificity"

Precision: When it predicts yes, how often is it correct?¶

TP/predicted yes - when a model predicts 1 or zero how many times is each predictio correct

Prevalence: How often does the yes condition actually occur in our sample?¶

actual yes/total - to check the class distribution.
